The paper discusses the performance evaluation of encounter-based networks, which are a type of wireless ad-hoc network. This topic falls under the category of computer networks (cs.NI). The paper specifically focuses on worm propagation and interactions, which is a topic related to computer security (cs.CR). The use of models and simulations to analyze the impact of node characteristics on worm propagation and interactions suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) or social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the use of mobile network measurements and analysis of the effectiveness of counter-worm protocols suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of information theory (cs.IT).
